hello I'm Nelson a technical customer
support associate here at the AWS office
in Dublin today I'm going to show you
how to use AWS cloud trail to track who
may change to your AWS resources and
infrastructure let's get
started after loging into the AWS
Management console navigate to the cloud
trail
console then in the navigation pane
choose
Trails here you can see the Amazon
Simply Storage service booked value for
the trail you want to view after you
choose the Amazon S3 booket link the
Amazon S3 console opens and shows the
booket look at the top level for the log
files choose the folder for the AWS
region where you want to review log
files the log file has a formatt name
that includes the year the log file was
published the month the log file was
published and the day the log file was
published select the file name and then
choose download this saves the file in a
compress
format finally unzip the file and then
use your favorite Json file viewer to
see the log the log file contains the
AWS identity and access management user
date and time of login and if the login
was
successful note if you have a Json
viewer added on installed you can view
the files directly in your
browser open the log file in the booket
to open a new browser window or tab the
Json displays in a readable format so
now you know how to use cloud trail to
track who may change your AWS resources
and
infrastructure thanks for watching and
help cloud computing from all of us here
